Date:9/24/2007 4:53:47 PM
From:E_K_S
Hi rllee - Same type of move for AAV up 5.46%. There is chatter that based on
the $CAN now at parity with the $US, their current reserves translate into a
NAV around $19.23 US. Also, the dividend distributions to US holders are higher
this month because of the $US conversion even though the $CAN payout has
remained unchanged. Some investors feel that the underlining assets are
significantly undervalued and have been buying AAV shares.

The big move IMO is yet to come. NG prices need to increase to better reflect
the longterm price of the equivalent $mmBTU for oil. Based on the chart below,
Natural gas is selling for about half its value from December. The price per
BTU s/b roughly the same for NG and oil. At current prices, NG is 56% less
expensive than oil for the equivalent amount of BTU energy.

http://www.econbrowser.com/archives/2006/05/natural_gas_and.html

The spot market prices (9/20/07) of the equivalent mmBTU: NG $6.18 vs oil
$14.14 mmBTU based on $82/barrel). (
http://tonto.eia.doe.gov/oog/info/ngw/ngupdate.asp ) That's 2.29x more for oil
than for the equivalent BTUs in NG.

Many factors make up the total cost of each resource but it appears that the
current ratio of 2.29 $Oil/$NG seems to be at the high end of their historical
level.

Some economist even argue that a premium should be paid for NG because of it's
efficiencies over oil (less pollution, limited refining & processing, easy to
transport through pipes). Many of the large integrated oil companies are
expanding their refinery capacity and making huge capital investments that add
to their total cost of production for oil which they do not have to do for NG.
Therefore, looking forward, these efficiencies for NG should further promote
switching from the use of oil to NG.

I believe crude oil prices need to go down or NG prices need to move higher.
Time will tell where this eventually adjusts out. My guess is NG prices will
move substantially higher in the longer term.

EKS
